## Networking Command

- ping
-> ping command is used to check the connectivity between two devices.

- netstat
-> netstat command is used to show active network connections and the status of ports on a system.

- ifconfig
-> ifconfig command is used to view network interface information such as IP address, MAC address, and status.

- NIC (Network interface card)
-> NIC is a network interface card that enables communication between a computer and a network.

- Traceroute 
-> traceroute command is used to trace the route and show all the intermediate hops between source and destination.

- Tracepath
-> tracepath command is used to trace the route and identify network hops between source and destination.

- mtr
-> mtr command combines the functionality of ping and traceroute to continuously monitor the network route and latency.

- nslookup
-> nslookup command is used to query DNS servers to obtain domain name or IP address information.

- telnet
-> telnet is a command used to remotely connect to another system over a network.

- hostname
-> hostname command is used to display the hostname of the system.

- iwconfig
-> iwconfig command is used to display and configure wireless network interfaces.

- ss
-> ss command is used to show information about active network connections, listening ports, and sockets.

- domain
-> A domain is a human-readable name used to identify a website, and DNS converts the domain name into an IP address.

- dig (domain information groper)
-> dig (Domain Information Groper) is a command used to retrieve DNS records such as IP address, name servers, and MX records.

- nc (netcat)
-> nc (netcat) is a networking utility used for debugging, testing, and transferring data between systems.

- arp (Address Resolution Protocol)
-> ARP (Address Resolution Protocol) is used to map IP addresses to MAC addresses on a local network.

- ifplugstatus
-> ifplugstatus command is used to show the link status of a network interface.





